SIMPLE: never
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Never
<hw>Nev"er</hw> <pr>(n⟦ecr⟧v"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>n⟦aemac⟧fre</ets>; <ets>ne</ets> not, no + <ets>⟦aemac⟧fre</ets>
ever.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not ever; not at any time; at no time,
whether past, present, or future.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Death still draws nearer, <qex>never</qex> seeming near.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In no degree; not in the least; not.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whosoever has a friend to guide him, may carry his eyes in another
man's head, and yet see <qex>never</qex> the worse.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And he answered him to <qex>never</qex> a word.</q> <rj><qau>Matt.
xxvii. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Never</xex> is much used in composition with
present participles to form adjectives, as in <xex>never</xex>-ceasing,
<xex>never</xex>-dying, <xex>never</xex>-ending,
<xex>never</xex>-fading, <xex>never</xex>-failing, etc., retaining its
usual signification.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Never a deal</b></col>, <cd>not a bit.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au> -- <col><b>Never so</b></col>,
<cd>as never before; more than at any other time, or in any other
circumstances; especially; particularly; -- now often expressed or
replaced by <altname>ever so</altname>.</cd>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<q>Ask me <qex>never so</qex> much dower and gift.</q> <rj><qau>Gen.
xxxiv. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<q>A fear of battery, . . . though <qex>never so</qex> well grounded, is
no duress.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>never-ending</ent>⟦br⟧
